{"id":1432,"date":"2016-06-08T13:25:23","date_gmt":"2016-06-08T12:25:23","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/www.edlab.org.uk\/?p=1432"},"modified":"2016-12-06T12:25:34","modified_gmt":"2016-12-06T12:25:34","slug":"funologist-project-create-non-linear-support-resource-sonic-pi-coding-music-software","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/funologist-project-create-non-linear-support-resource-sonic-pi-coding-music-software\/","title":{"rendered":"EdLab Spark: Create a non-linear support resource for Sonic Pi coding music software"},"content":{"rendered":"<p>Sonic Pi is computer software which creates music with simple lines of code. Designed by a \u2018live coding\u2019 enthusiast called <strong>Sam Aaron with the support of the Rasberry Pi Foundation<\/strong>, this simple but revolutionary approach has created a new way for young and adults alike to learn coding concepts in an extremely engaging (sometimes compulsive way).<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-914\" src=\"http:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/wp-content\/uploads\/sites\/64\/2016\/01\/sonic_pi_music011-800x597.jpg\" alt=\"sonic_pi_music011\" width=\"800\" height=\"597\" srcset=\"https:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/wp-content\/uploads\/sites\/64\/2016\/01\/sonic_pi_music011-800x597.jpg 800w, https:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/wp-content\/uploads\/sites\/64\/2016\/01\/sonic_pi_music011-300x224.jpg 300w, https:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/wp-content\/uploads\/sites\/64\/2016\/01\/sonic_pi_music011-768x573.jpg 768w, https:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/wp-content\/uploads\/sites\/64\/2016\/01\/sonic_pi_music011.jpg 1200w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>In our Funologist experiments with Sonic Pi so far, we have found the most interesting results happen when participants do not have handouts telling them what to do. Providing them with a \u2018linear\u2019 hand out often means that those taking part follow the direction given to them rather than being led by their interest.<\/p>\n<p>Conversely, a starting point and some quick references are handy. \u00a0As we ask more students to support Sonic Pi workshops, we need a non-linear resource to help the process.<\/p>\n<p>We are very open to different suggestions but as a starting point we are thinking that a large poster with different areas and possibilities could be a good choice. This poster should be visually appealing, encourage experimental play and also be easy to print and to edit.<\/p>\n<p><!--more--><\/p>\n<p>One End Goal would be a resource to help deliver Sonic Pi workshops in a way that provides a minimum of traditional \u201cinstruction\u201d. It would also be good to build a public log of observations from workshop facilitators and helpers which communicates helpful ideas on this approach.<\/p>\n<p>Key concepts here involve non-linear learning and alternatives to the banking model of education. Tinkering as a pedagogy is increasing in popularity especially for learning experiences outside of the school curriculum.<\/p>\n<p><b>More Information:<br \/>\n<\/b>To get involved in this project, or to work on a challenge which supports the development of this project, contact m.chesterman @mmu.ac.uk or edlab @mmu.ac.uk<\/p>\n<p><b>Key Partner:<\/b> Primary Secondary and Home Educator groups, Sonic Pi development team<a href=\"http:\/\/www.mix-d.org\/about\"><br \/>\n<\/a><b>Key Words:<\/b> Sonic pi, Music, Coding, non-linear resources, exploratory learning, tinkering<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Sonic Pi is computer software which creates music with simple lines of code. Designed by a \u2018live coding\u2019 enthusiast called Sam Aaron with the support of the Rasberry Pi Foundation, this simple but revolutionary approach has created a new way for young and adults alike to learn coding concepts in an extremely engaging (sometimes compulsive [&hellip;]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":29,"featured_media":904,"comment_sta